377 total cases: 24 deceased, 16 isolated and 337 recovered

The Massachusetts Department of Public Health has notified the town of Winthrop of three additional residents affected by COVID-19.
Visit WinthropCOVID19.com for regular updates of COVID-19 in our community.

Winthrop Public Health and Clinical Services
September 2 at 4:13 PM ·

If you recently went to one of the Winthrop #stopthespread testing sites and are wondering where your results are, look out for an email from careevolve@LKNotification.com. It may ask you to register to receive your results. This is a safe email address, and will have your results ready for you. If the email is not in your inbox, it may have been sent to your spam folder.

Results will generally return within 24-36 hours from the time of testing, but there may be some delays in getting your results to you. We apologize for any confusion this may have caused and thank you for your patience!

For any concerns about your results, please contact the Winthrop Department of Public Health at (617) 593-5848 or call the 24/7 Resulting Call line directly at 617-765-0176.

post_text:
Donovans Beach is currently closed due to high test results.

The beach is being retested and will reopen when normal levels resume.

G & L Labs in Quincy, MA conducts weekly tests of the water quality of 5 beaches in Winthrop for levels of Enterococci which is an indicator of fecal pollution and possible enteric pathogens. When the level exceeds 104 MPN (most probable number)/100 mL, the Town of Winthrop closes the beach. High levels are usually due to heavy rainfall and usually return to normal levels after a retest.
Please take precaution and temporarily refrain from swimming in closed beaches until levels return to safe conditions. Thank you for your cooperation.

MILLER FIELD PUBLIC ACCESS BEGINS WEDNESDAY JULY 29TH

Monday – Friday 7:00 AM – 10:00 AM
Weekends 9:00 AM – 12:00 PM

• Residents using the track must adhere to all posted rules and regulations.
• All persons entering the field will be required to give their name, phone number and email address for Public Health contact tracing purposes.
• Masks or face coverings must be worn.
• Hand sanitizer will be on site and must be used prior to entry.
• There will be NO access to the field house bathrooms.
• NO food is allowed.
• Residents can bring water. However, no trash receptacles will be available. Please carry in/carry out all items.
• All persons are must maintain social distancing of 6 feet between others.
• Miller Field will close for inclement weather.

Library patrons can make their online requests via our catalog. Click on the “login to your account” button that’s located on the front left side of the home page. Select the items you’d like to check out and we’ll contact you when they’re ready and to schedule a pickup time that works for you.
A library card number and pin is required to log in. Email wth@noblenet.org email if you need a library card or assistance logging in.
Patrons can also call us at (617) 846-1703 and leave a message.
Visit www.winthroppubliclibrary.org to learn more.

Stop the Spread! Stay Healthy!
We remind residents to be taking the following steps as a precaution:
Maintain social distances.
Wear face coverings when in public places or around others.
Avoid gatherings of groups of 10 or more people.
Wash hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.
Monitor children for good handwashing etiquette.
Use alcohol-based hand sanitizer and gels.
Avoid close contact with those who are sick.
Stay home when you are sick.
Cover your cough and sneeze with your inner elbow.
Clean and disinfect surfaces frequently.

post_text:
Winthrop Visioning 2030

Community input is needed! What is your future vision for Winthrop? The MAPC and the Town of Winthrop is seeking community input on how to develop a future vision for the Town. The Winthrop Visioning 20030 open house includes an informational presentation on shorter-range, daily, quality-of-life and operational topics, as well as “big ideas” for more potentially transformative ideas in the future. Community brainstorming exercises will also include a prioritization of both of these types of ideas so that the Town can have a clear set of next steps.

Visit the Online Open House “Room” to provide your feedback. For more information visit mapc.ma/winthrop2030.

post_text:
May Street Sweeping Starts Monday, May 18

The Town of Winthrop conducts Street Sweeping operations on the last full week of the month (last week with a Friday) from April through October between 7:00 AM and 4:00 PM on the day of a street's trash collection. If there is a holiday on the week sweeping would normally occur, sweeping is done a week early. May street sweeping is scheduled for May 18 to 22* one week early due to the Memorial Day holiday on May 25.

Town ordinance prohibits parking in a manner that impedes the street sweeper. Violation of the street sweeping ordinance carries a $40.00 fine, and your vehicle can be towed. Enforcement of the street sweeping regulations will resume on May 18.
The remaining 2020 street sweeping dates are:
June 22-26 (week of the 22nd)
July 27-31 (week of the 27th)
Aug. 24-28 (week of the 24th)
Sep. 21-25 (week of the 21st)
Oct. 26-30 (week of the 26th)

https://www.town.winthrop.ma.us/home/news/may-street-sweeping-starts-monday-may-18

WINTHROP COMMUNITY FOOD BANK

The Food Bank will continue accepting donations Monday-Thursday from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. at the FRONT loop of the Cummings School across from the Fire Station. The Food Bank is in need of non-perishable items such as cereals, canned goods, pasta, bread, peanut butter and jelly, toiletries and paper products. Items without an expiration date cannot be accepted.

The Winthrop Community Food Bank will be distributing food by delivery only. There will be NO in-person pick-up at the Cummings Elementary School. If you are in need of food, please email: WinthropFoodBank@town.winthrop.ma.us. Please provide your name, address, phone number and the number of people in your household. If your need is urgent, please call the Emergency Operations Center at 617-539-5848.

Typically, Massport would conduct an in-person project overview presentation to community groups. Given the current health climate we find ourselves in, we’d like to take this opportunity to invite you and your membership to a virtual Runway 9/27 rehabilitation presentation on Thursday, May 7th, at 6:30pm, utilizing the GoToWebinar software.

If you are interested in attending this virtual presentation, we ask that you go to https://attendee.gotowebinar.com/register/995392681091150604 and register. Center Business District Infrastructure Improvements Construction Updates April 9, 2020

As construction progresses for the Center Business Infrastructure Project, we remain committed to continuous water service to all homes and businesses.
If any resident experiences discolored water, it is not harmful and will clear if you run your cold water in the bathtub for several minutes.

This discoloration is simply iron that gets stirred up when water is diverted or flow direction is changed.
We recommend the use of a bathtub so aerators in faucets aren't affected.

This is especially true for survivors living with disabilities, immigrants, young people, LGBTQQI+ communities and survivors of color. If you or someone you know is experiencing violence, you are not alone. Service providers across Massachusetts continue to provide critical healthcare, housing, and economic support for survivors. Donations Accepted Today!
Winthrop Community Food Bank
• The Food Bank will be accepting donations on Mondays and Wednesdays from 11am to 1pm. The Food Bank is in need of non-perishable items such as canned goods, pasta, peanut butter and jelly, toiletries and paper products. Items without an expiration date cannot be accepted.
• Food will be distributed to Winthrop residents in need from 11am to 1pm on Tuesdays and Thursdays. Please have an ID showing Winthrop residency with you. Please remain in your vehicle; Food Bank volunteers will place items into your car. The volunteers are practicing social distancing and we respectfully ask you to do the same.
• The Food Bank is located at the rear (School Street) entrance to the Cummings Elementary School.
• If you are elderly, or homebound, please contact the Emergency Operations Center at 617-539-5848 so delivery arrangements can be made.
• For questions about the Food Bank or donations, please contact Matt Rodes at mrodes@town.winthrop.ma.us.

post_text:
Canned Good Needed!

The Food Bank is requesting canned goods, pasta, non-perishables, sealed baby formula, toiletries and paper products including toilet paper, tissues, napkins, and paper towels.

Collection days are Monday and Wednesday from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. No need to get out of your car. Drop off is located at the loop on School Street behind the Cummings School.

Food will be distributed on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 11am-1pm. If you are elderly, or homebound, please contact the Emergency Operations Center at 617-539-5848 so delivery arrangements can be made. We appreciate your cooperation in helping to make this process orderly and efficient.

For more information about the Food Bank or volunteer opportunities, please contact Matt Rodes at mrodes@town.winthrop.ma.us.

post_text:
Town of Winthrop Mourns Commonwealth's First COVID-19 Death

Winthrop officials wish to issue the following statement to the community:

We are deeply saddened to announce that a Winthrop resident has died as a result of his contracting COVID-19, the illness associated with the novel coronavirus.

You will hear from the media and from the state and federal government that the victim was an 87-year-old man with underlying health conditions. The latter is as irrelevant to us as community leaders as it is to the family of our departed resident. The fact is that this terrible virus has taken a life in our community, and that loss of life gives each of us pause and fills us with sorrow.

We are aware that our resident is the first patient to die from COVID-19 in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts. We have one other resident who was diagnosed last week and continues to recover at home.

We relay from the family that they are deeply saddened and have requested privacy during this most difficult time, and we ask that everyone respect their wishes during this difficult time.

You can now call 211 from a cellphone or landline for real-time COVID-19 updates and referrals including:•COVID-19 prevention, treatment, and symptom
Information about testing
•Guidance for people returning from travel
The 211 hotline is available 24 hours a day and can provide information in 150 languages. When you call 211 you will hear an automated message and should press 2-6 for COVID-19 information. You can also access 211 resources through the Massachusetts 211 website.

post_text:
Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) Info

The risk of Coronavirus (COVID-19) remains low in our community.

We remind residents to be taking the following steps as a precaution:
- Wash hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.
- Monitor children for good handwashing etiquette.
- Use alcohol-based hand sanitizer and gels.
- Avoid close contact with those who are sick.
- Stay home when you are sick.
- Cover your cough and sneeze with your inner elbow.
- Clean and disinfect surfaces frequently.
- In addition, if you have traveled to Italy, Iran, China, South Korea, and/or Japan we ask that you Self-Quarantine for 14 days upon arrival to the United States.

As this is an evolving situation, we are committed to keeping our community informed and updated. Many questions have arisen about self-quarantine. Please reference info below or call the Winthrop Department of Public Health @ 617-846-1852 x1061.
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/

Stop by the 10th Annual Shamrock Splash to support the Friends of Winthrop Beach's team! We are trying to bring even more events to Winthrop Beach, but can't do it without your help. If you can't SPLASH, then please donate to our Save The Harbor - Save The Bay/Winthrop Beach page. If you are splashing, cost is $20 to participate and you get: beer, chowdah, and participate in contests and raffles for a chance to win a free round trip ticket anywhere Jet Blue flies....the date is Sun, March 8th, at 10 am at the BCYF Curley Community Center in South Boston - free parking along the beach! Contact Rose Mazzuchelli or Barbara Bishop for more details.

For more information about Save the Harbor/Save the Bay and the great work they do to restore, protect and share Boston Harbor and the region’s public beaches, please visit their website at www.savehtheharbor.org, their blog “Sea, Sand & Sky” at blog.savetheharbor.org, or follow savetheharbor on Facebook, Twitter, and Instagram.

Center Business District Infrastructure Improvements Project Updates
Informational Community Meeting 3/12!

Financing for the infrastructure project in the Center Business District (CBD) has been approved and construction will occur in 2020 and 2021. This is a critical infrastructure project for the Town and will result in a system that works better for the entire community. Although this will be a large undertaking, the Town believes that it is a necessary project and we appreciate the understanding and appreciation of the community.

To view the most updated version of the timeline of work for the Center Business District Infrastructure Project, please visit https://stories.opengov.com/winthropma/published/cqK8p3KPe
Project updates will be posted regularly at https://www.town.winthrop.ma.us/winthrop-projects-plans-and-presentations/pages/center-business-district-infrastructure-improvements

VETERANS SERVICES NEWS

The next Veterans/Families Food Banks will take place on Wednesday, March 4th at the American Legion (next to Town Hall). Pick-up is from 10:00-11:00. If you are new to our Food Bank, then you must pre-register with Veteran Services.

Attention Veterans: There is a local scam going around calling Veterans and asking for personal information with promises to get rid of debt, help with claims and other bogus offers. The calls are coming from (617) 752-6891. Please DO NOT give him/her any of your personal information!

Vietnam Veterans Books are available at Winthrop Veteran Services. The books are beautiful hardcover book covering the Vietnam War, titled: 50th Commemoration - A Time To Honor. Vietnam Vets have priority in receiving these books.

Veteran Services does all Memorial Dedications on the Sunday prior to Memorial Day. If you would like a Veteran who has passed, to have a Memorial Dedication, please contact Winthrop Veteran Services as there are requirements that must be met.

https://www.town.winthrop.ma.us/veterans-services

post_text:
Wednesday, February 12, 2020 will be the last day to register to vote for the Presidential Primary Election on Tuesday, March 3, 2020.

The Town Clerk’s Office will be open on February 12th from 8am to 8pm for citizen convenience.

The only requirements to register to vote are that you are a citizen of the United States, a resident of Winthrop and will be 18 years old on or before Election Day. You may register in the Town Clerk’s Office, or you may request a mail-in registration form by phone or visit https://www.sec.state.ma.us/OVR/

Those registering to vote using mail-in registration forms must have their forms postmarked no later than February 12th in order to vote in the Presidential Primary. This is a primary election and the law only allows a voter to receive a ballot in the party in which you are registered UNLESS you are UNENROLLED. Read below for more information, and if you want to change your party – THE DEADLINE IS FEB.
12, 2020

post_text:
Point Shirley Power Outage Update:

At approximately 4:30 PM today heavy winds knocked down telephone poles on Shirley Street resulting in many National Grid electric customers to be without power. Chief Flanagan has been informed by National Grid that due to the extent of the damage and the continuing strong winds, the majority of the customers who currently are without power will not see their power restored until as late as mid-morning tomorrow. Anyone seeking shelter, or has any other emergency needs resulting from this outage, please call 911. At this time there is not a shelter opened, but one will be opened if needed. The Winthrop Fire Department has an Engine and crew stationed in Church Square by the Point Shirley Association Building and will remain as long as Shirley St is blocked, and until the power is restored.

VETERANS SERVICES NEWS

The next Veterans/Families Food Banks will take place on Wednesday, March 4th at the American Legion (next to Town Hall). Pick-up is from 10:00-11:00. If you are new to our Food Bank, then you must pre-register with Veteran Services.

Attention Veterans: There is a local scam going around calling Veterans and asking for personal information with promises to get rid of debt, help with claims and other bogus offers. The calls are coming from (617) 752-6891. Please DO NOT give him/her any of your personal information!

Vietnam Veterans Books are available at Winthrop Veteran Services. The books are beautiful hardcover book covering the Vietnam War, titled: 50th Commemoration - A Time To Honor. Vietnam Vets have priority in receiving these books.

Veteran Services does all Memorial Dedications on the Sunday prior to Memorial Day. If you would like a Veteran who has passed, to have a Memorial Dedication, please contact Winthrop Veteran Services as there are requirements that must be met.

AVAILABLE FOR PURCHASE

There are two ways to get a license:
1. Do it immediately in a few minutes online at
http://www.town.winthrop.ma.us/town-clerk/pages/dog-licenses

2. Wait until the middle of January for the annual census to be mailed to your home, on the bottom will be a mail in slip, you can send in check and proof of rabies in the same envelope as the census and tag will be mailed to you.

Late fees begin April 1, 2020.
Please note the Town Clerk’s Office does not save Rabies information, nor do we have it if you used the Town sponsored rabies clinic. It is the responsibility of the pet owner to have medical information for your animals. Please contact the Town Clerk’s office with any questions.

WINTHROP FIREFIGHTERS LOCAL 1070
SANTA MAKES HIS ANNUAL PLANS WITH WINTHROP FIREFIGHTERS

Santa Claus has once again contacted the Winthrop Firefighters to make his plans for visiting the town of Winthrop!
On Tuesday, December 24th (Christmas Eve) Santa will be escorted through the streets of Winthrop by the Winthrop firefighters.

Rain or snow will not keep Santa and the firefighters from completing this annual tradition, but cars parked illegally or parked on or close to corners can keep Santa from certain streets. So please for Santa and his helpers, work with your neighbors in making sure that Santa’s route remains open. If you are new to Winthrop or have never seen this special procession, do not miss it. It is a truly spectacular event that rivals none.

Winthrop, MA Police Department is with Samantha Faro.
December 11, 2019 at 4:45 PM ·

Today Winthrop Officers, Andrew Biggio, (founder of the Boston’s Wounded Vet Run) Samantha Petersen and Richard Ferrino Jr., escorted sixteen WWII veterans back to Belgium for the 75th Anniversary of the Battle of the Bulge. While at the cemetery In Luxembourg, they visited Winthrop’s own Joe Madona of the 101st Airborne, who gave his life in the battle. Joe was only 27-years-old when he was killed in action. He hailed from Shirley St in town.

Thanksgiving Pie Sale
St John's Episcopal Church is selling delicious Thanksgiving pies to benefit Community Servings, a local non-profit that delivers healthy meals to critically-ill, homebound individuals in Winthrop and throughout eastern Massachusetts. Pies cost $30 and are prepared by some of Boston's top chefs - best of all, each pie sold funds an entire week’s worth of nutritious home-delivered meals to a person who is too ill to shop or cook for themselves. Please order online at www.WinthropPies.com. All orders will be available for pick up the day before Thanksgiving, between 2:00 and 7:00 pm, at the St. John's Episcopal Church Parish Hall.

text:
CURBSIDE LEAF PICKUP

Curbside leaf pickup will be conducted in Winthrop on the following 2 dates:
• Saturday, November 16th
• Saturday, December 21st
Leaves must be placed on the curb in paper bags or barrels. Leaves in plastic bags will not be picked up.

YARD WASTE DROPOFF

Winthrop's green waste drop-off site is located at the end of Kennedy Drive, where residents may bring their yard waste.
The facility is open from April 13th through December 14th.

The hours of operation are Fridays from 9:00 am to Noon and 3:00 pm to 6:00 pm and Saturdays from 9:00 to noon and 1:00 pm to 3:00 pm.

Please contact the DPW at (617) 846-1341 with any questions.

https://www.town.winthrop.ma.us/trash-recycling/pages/yard-waste-drop-facility

post_text:
DOG LICENSES FOR THE YEAR 2020
AVAILABLE FOR PURCHASE
BEGINNING JANUARY 2, 2020.

There are two ways to get a license:
1. Do it immediately in a few minutes online at
http://www.town.winthrop.ma.us/town-clerk/pages/dog-licenses

2. Wait until the middle of January for the annual census to be mailed to your home, on the bottom will be a mail in slip, you can send in check and proof of rabies in the same envelope as the census and tag will be mailed to you.

Late fees begin April 1, 2020.

Please note the Town Clerk’s Office does not save Rabies information, nor do we have it if you used the Town sponsored rabies clinic. It is the responsibility of the pet owner to have medical information for your animals. Please contact the Town Clerk’s office with any questions.

Winthrop, MA Police Department
October 30, 2019 at 10:05 PM ·

The administrative staff for the Town have been monitoring reports for tomorrow night. The latest reports for the Boston area has the heaviest rain activity late Thursday night into Friday morning. Winds are highest over the islands and Cape Cod. Given this information Halloween will go on as previously planned. However, we are encouraging all parents to stay abreast of the weather reports and make a decision based on their own family situations taken into account all relevant facts and the ages of their own children, prior to trick or treating. No one knows better what is best for a particular child than the child’s parents. Please read attached Halloween safety tips. Thank you Chief Terence Delehanty
